This paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category as it deals with the study of human behavior and compliance in hand hygiene. It could also belong to the Cybernetics (cs.CY) sub-category as it uses predictive models to analyze and control human behavior. Additionally, it could be classified under Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) as it examines the impact of social factors on hand hygiene compliance. The paper also uses statistical models to analyze data, which could place it under the Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) sub-category. Finally, the study involves multiple facilities and factors, which could make it relevant to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
